{"title_page": "Commandant's Service", "text_new": "[[File:USSR of Commandant subdivision emblem.jpg|thumb|Red shield arm patch of the soviet commandant's Service]]\n'''Commandant's Service''' was the name for the [[military police]] of some [[Warsaw Pact]]<ref name=\"Warsaw Pact Ground Forces p 49\">Warsaw Pact Ground Forces, Gordan Rottman, Osprey Publishing Elite 10, p 49 Coprwyrite 1987 {{ISBN|0-85045-730-0}}</ref> and other armies. Its principal duties were providing garrison security and traffic control. It is not to be confused with a similar organization called [[Traffic Regulator]]s operated by the Transport Troops of the [[Rear Services]].\n\n==Soviet Union/Russia==\n[[File:Gorky Automobile Plant in Nizhniy Novgorod (23).jpg|thumb|[[GAZ Sobol]] Commandant's Service van]]\nThe ''Komendantskaya sluzhba'' (Russian: \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430) or 'komendatura' (Ru:\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0430) in the [[Soviet Army|Soviet]] and [[Russian Army|Russian]] militaries were designated by a red shield on one or both arms bearing a yellow letter \"K\", plain red [[shoulder board]]s and a white helmet bearing a red star and broad red circumferential stripe.<ref name=\"GoogleBooks-8203247\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1GBAYgEACAAJ |title=Soviet Uniforms and Militaria 1917 - 1991 in Colour Photographs |isbn=978-1-84797-260-6 |publisher=Crowood Press |accessdate=May 23, 2014 |year=2011 |pages=102, 148 |edition=illustrated |first=L\u00e1szl\u00f3 |last=B\u00e9k\u00e9si |origyear=2000}}</ref> These helmets were generally painted at the unit level <ref name=\"GoogleBooks-8203247\"/><ref>Russian Helmets:from Kaska to Stalshlyem 1916-2001 by Robert W Clawson, pgs 115 - 117, R. JamesBender Publishing Copyright 2002 {{ISBN|0-912138-90-4}}</ref>  The ''komendatura'' are being replaced by the newly established [[Military Police (Russia)|Military Police]] (Ru:\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 or Voennaya politsiya or VP).\n\nAt one time the komendatura officers wore a black cloth or leather uniform with white helmets and gloves, and belts and holsters.<ref name=\"russianwarrior.com\">http://www.russianwarrior.com/STMMain.htm?1969_uniform_army_komandant.htm&1</ref><ref name=\"GoogleBooks-8203247\"/><ref name=\"GoogleBooks-6794957\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PQgWAAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover |title=Russian Security and Paramilitary Forces since 1991 |isbn=978-1-78096-107-1 |date=August 20, 2013 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |accessdate=May 23, 2014 |pages=43\u20134 |editor=Mark Galeotti |first=Mark |last=Galeotti}}</ref><ref>THE SOVIET ARMY: Specialized Warfare and Rear Area Support 'Field Manual 100-2-2 pgs 13-23, Headquarters Department of the Army Washington. DC, 16 July 1984</ref><ref name=\"russianwarrior.com\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Bulgaria==\n\nThe Commandment Service is part of the [[Ministry of Defence (Bulgaria)|Ministry of Defence]], located in [[Sofia, Bulgaria|Sofia]] and is in charge of real estate management, transportation, library services, documentation publishing and communications support for the central administration of the MoD, transportation support to the immediate MoD personnel, classified information, cryptographic, and perimeter security for the MoD administration buildings.\n\n==East Germany==\n{{main|Commandant's Service (East Germany)}}\nThe [[East German Army]] Commandant's Service was called the ''Kommandantendienst'' or KD, in addition to traffic control and military police duties it performed courier services.<ref name=\"Warsaw Pact Ground Forces p 49\"/> The ''Kommandantendienst'' wore a white stripe on their helmet and a white [[Sam Browne belt|cross strap and belt]], [[handgun holster]] and gloves.<ref>Warsaw Pact Ground Forces, Gordan Rottman, Osprey Publishing Elite 10, Color plate A {{ISBN|0-85045-730-0}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Commandant]]\n* [[Military Police]]\n* [[Regimental Police]]\n* [[Unit Police]]\n* [[Traffic Regulator]]\n\n[[Category:Military police]]\n[[Category:Combat support occupations]]\n[[Category:Military law]]\n\n\n{{mil-unit-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:USSR of Commandant subdivision emblem.jpg|thumb|Red shield arm patch of the soviet commandant's Service]]\n'''Commandant's Service''' was the name for the [[military police]] of some [[Warsaw Pact]]<ref name=\"Warsaw Pact Ground Forces p 49\">Warsaw Pact Ground Forces, Gordan Rottman, Osprey Publishing Elite 10, p 49 Coprwyrite 1987 {{ISBN|0-85045-730-0}}</ref> and other armies. Its principal duties were providing garrison security and traffic control. It is not to be confused with a similar organization called [[Traffic Regulator]]s operated by the Transport Troops of the [[Rear Services]].\n\n==Soviet Union/Russia==\n[[File:Gorky Automobile Plant in Nizhniy Novgorod (23).jpg|thumb|[[GAZ Sobol]] Commandant's Service van]]\nThe ''Komendantskaya sluzhba'' (Russian: \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430) or 'komendatura' (Ru:\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0430) in the [[Soviet Army|Soviet]] and [[Russian Army|Russian]] militaries were designated by a red shield on one or both arms bearing a yellow letter \"K\", plain red [[shoulder board]]s and a white helmet bearing a red star and broad red circumferential stripe.<ref name=\"GoogleBooks-8203247\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1GBAYgEACAAJ |title=Soviet Uniforms and Militaria 1917 - 1991 in Colour Photographs |isbn=978-1-84797-260-6 |publisher=Crowood Press |accessdate=May 23, 2014 |year=2011 |pages=102, 148 |edition=illustrated |first=L\u00e1szl\u00f3 |last=B\u00e9k\u00e9si |origyear=2000}}</ref> These helmets were generally painted a